==================
| String Methods |
==================
👉 String methods are built-in functions used to perform different operations on strings such as changing case, 
   searching, replacing, splitting, formatting, and checking string content.

1. upper() -> Converts all characters of a string into uppercase letters.

  text = "python programming"
  print(text.upper())

Output
PYTHON PROGRAMMING

2. lower() -> Converts all characters into lowercase letters.

  text = "PYTHON"
  print(text.lower())

Output
python

3. title() -> Converts the first letter of every word into uppercase.

  text = "python programming language"
  print(text.title())

Output
Python Programming Language

4. capitalize() -> Converts only the first character of the string into uppercase.

  text = "python programming"
  print(text.capitalize())

Output
Python programming

5. swapcase() -> Changes uppercase letters to lowercase and lowercase letters to uppercase.

  text = "PyThOn"
  print(text.swapcase())

Output
pYtHoN

6. casefold() -> Converts a string to lowercase for case-insensitive comparisons.

  text = "HELLO"
  print(text.casefold())

Output
hello

7. strip() -> Removes spaces from both sides of the string.

  text = "   Python   "
  print(text.strip())

Output
Python

8. lstrip() -> Removes spaces from the left side.

  text = "   Python"
  print(text.lstrip())

Output
Python

9. rstrip() -> Removes spaces from the right side.

  text = "Python   "
  print(text.rstrip())

Output
Python

10. replace() -> Replaces one substring with another.

  text = "I Love Java"
  print(text.replace("Java", "Python"))

Output
I Love Python

11. find() -> Returns the index of the first occurrence of a substring. Returns -1 if not found.

  text = "Python"
  print(text.find("t"))

Output
2

12. index() -> Returns the index of a substring. Raises an error if not found.

  text = "Python"
  print(text.index("o"))

Output
4

Difference Between find() and index()
--------------------------------------
find()	index() -> Returns -1 if not found	Raises ValueError if not found Safer to use	Use when value is guaranteed

13. count() -> Counts the number of occurrences of a substring.

  text = "banana"
  print(text.count("a"))

Output
3

14. startswith() -> Checks whether the string starts with a given value.

  text = "Python"
  print(text.startswith("Py"))

Output
True

15. endswith() -> Checks whether the string ends with a given value.

  text = "Python"
  print(text.endswith("on"))

Output
True

16. split() -> Splits a string into a list.

  text = "Python Java C++"
  print(text.split())

Output
['Python', 'Java', 'C++']

17. join() -> Joins elements of an iterable into a single string.

  languages = ["Python", "Java", "C++"]
  print(" - ".join(languages))

Output
Python - Java - C++

18. isalpha() -> Returns True if all characters are alphabets.

  print("Python".isalpha())

Output
True

19. isdigit() -> Returns True if all characters are digits.

  print("12345".isdigit())

Output
True

20. isnumeric() -> Returns True if all characters are numeric.

  print("123".isnumeric())

Output
True

21. isalnum() -> Returns True if the string contains only letters and numbers.

  print("Python123".isalnum())

Output
True

22. islower() -> Returns True if all letters are lowercase.

  print("python".islower())

Output
True

23. isupper() -> Returns True if all letters are uppercase.

  print("PYTHON".isupper())

Output
True

24. istitle() -> Returns True if every word starts with an uppercase letter.

  print("Python Programming".istitle())

Output
True

25. isspace() -> Returns True if the string contains only whitespace.

  print("   ".isspace())

Output
True

26. center() -> Centers the string within the specified width.

  print("Python".center(20, "-"))

Output
-------Python-------

27. ljust() -> Left-aligns the string.

  print("Python".ljust(15, "*"))

Output
Python*********

28. rjust() -> Right-aligns the string.

  print("Python".rjust(15, "*"))

Output
*********Python

29. zfill() -> Pads the string with leading zeros.

  print("25".zfill(5))

Output
00025

30. format() -> Formats values into a string.

  name = "Mridul"
  marks = 95
  print("Name: {}, Marks: {}".format(name, marks))

Output
Name: Mridul, Marks: 95

31. encode() -> Converts a string into bytes.

  text = "Python"
  print(text.encode())

Output
b'Python'

